column168: The drum that failed was brought to the loading dock on a pallet. The pallet was placed on the rear of the box van. The driver rolled/ slid the drum off of the pallet onto the trailer floor to properly secure it with other drums in the shipment. The drum began to leak after moving it off of the pallet. Absorbent pads and speedi-dry were used to control and contain the leak until the drum could be overpacked. The overpacked drum and spill clean up residue will be shipped for proper disposal. It is believed that corrosion and metal fatigue caused the drum failure. We will continue careful examination of all packages for corrosion and metal fatigue that could result in package failure.

column168: On 11/11/98, at 19:00 hours, an Edwards Oil tank transport was at the LTV, Erie Mining Co. location in Hoyt Lakes, Minnesota. The transport driver was transferring diesel fuel to the TK #501 fuel station when a hose fitting unexpectedly released and came open, spilling diesel fuel onto the on site soil. The spill was immediately diked and soaked up with absorbent pads. The contaminated soil was then removed for de-contamination by personnel from LTV, Erie Mining Co. The faulty hose fitting has been repaired.

column168: Driver unhooked 1" hose to the customers storage tank and started the unloading process. Driver was at the front of the truck when he saw an ammonia cloud; he pulled the ESO; got into the cab and disengaged the PTO and went to the other side to close the discharge valve and put on his gas mask to close the valves on the rear of the truck and on the customers tank in order to minimize the loss of NH. The gasket on the hose reel swivel was made for LPG and was not compatible with ammonia. The correct gasket has been installed and will verify compatibility of any future material.

column25: W R R ENVIRONMENTAL SVCS CO
column168: PTL driver stopped in Breezewood, Pennsylvania truckstop to eat. Upon returning to his truck, driver discovered that there was product leaking out of the trailer door. The driver called Chemtrec and the local fire department. PTL contacted our insurance company and an adjustor was sent to the scene. The fire department determined that 19 pails overturned inside of the trailer allowing the product to leak around the lid. The fire department took care of the spill and placed all of the product in an overpack drum on the back of the trailer. They also placed absorb dry on the floor of the trailer and requested that we let it air out for two to three hours before the driver continues, which the driver did. The driver delivered to the consignee the next day and the load was refused due to the absorb dry that was on the floor. We contacted a local clean up crew located in the area, so that our drive could take the trailer to them for clean up. The trailer was off-loaded and cleaned. The clean up crew is responsible for the disposal. Our shipment was then accepted and the driver continued on.

column168: DERAILMENT OF 7 CARS IN TRAIN Q31703 NEAR THE COMMUNITY OF HENDERSON, WV RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF 3100 GALLONS OR 325600 LBS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE ACID WAS RELEASED FROM TWO CARS; UTLX 130155, WHICH CAME TO REST PARALLEL WITH THE TRACK STRUCTURE, WITH THE TOP APPERTANCES AT A 4 O'CLOCK POSITION HAD THE AIR LINE VALVE BROKEN OFF AND RELEASED AN ESTIMATED 2750 GALLONS AND UTLX 130007 WHICH ALSO CAME TO REST PARALLEL TO THE TRACK STRUCTURE WITH THE TOP APPERTANCE AT A 5 O'CLOCK POSITION HAD THE LIQUID VALVE BENT AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE UP AND THE BLIND FLANGE PUSHED SLIGHTLY ASKEW WHEN IT CAME TO REST ON A SIDE FRAME, RELEASING AN ESTIMATED 350 GALLONS. THE OPENING IN UTLX 130155 WAS PLUGGED WITH WOOD COVERED WITH RUBBER AND THE FLANGE ON UTLX 130007 WAS REALIGNED AND TIGHTENED, HOWEVER, THE SEAL WAS NOT 100%.  BOTH CARS WERE RERAILED AND MOVED WITH THE FRA APPROVAL TO LOCAL CHEMICAL PLANT AND TRANSFERRED BY THE SHIPPER TO TANK TRUCKS.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT WAS MITIGATED BY REMOVING THE FREE PRODUCT WITH A VACUUM TRUCK, 600 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED AND 134.65 TONS OF SOIL WERE EXCAVATED.

column168: THE PRODUCT WAS LOADED BY THE SHIPPER AT 0200 HOURS ON 10 NOVEMBER. 98, THE PRODUCT IS BOTTOM LOADED AND REQUIRES THAT THE VALVE BE BLED OFF AFTER THE LOADING IS COMPLETED.  THE LOADER FAILED TO FOLLOW THIS PROCEDURES PROPERLY.  THEREFORE, PRODUCT WAS LEFT IN THE EXTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THIS WAS COMPOUNDED BY AN IMPROPERLY INSTALLED GASKET IN THE EXTERNAL/INTERNAL VALVE FLANGE CONNECTION. THE DRIVER TOOK HIS BREAK AT THE BEAVERDAM SPEEDWAY TRUCK PLAZA AT ABOUT 0300 HOURS.  AT ABOUT 0800 A SLIGHT LEAK(DRIP) WAS DISCOVERED BY A PLAZA EMPLOYEE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND ESTABLISHED A "HOT" ZONE.  MAINTENANCE SUPPORT ARRIVED AND REPLACED THE GASKET AND INSTALLED A NEW EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE PRODUCT RESIDUE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE.  THE INCIDENT WAS ENDED AT 1030 HRS ON 10NOV98.  THREE SPEEDWAY EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED ABOUT BREATHING FUMES AND WERE TAKEN TO LIMA MEMORIAL HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.

column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE A DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TANKER HE ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN A FILTER WITHOUT TURNING OFF THE PUMP, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE HOSE ALLOWING 200 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL,170 GALLONS WENT INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WHILE 30 GALLONS WENT INTO AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE SPILL INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WAS VACUUMED UP INTO A VAC TRUCK. THE MATERIAL THAT WENT INTO THE PARKING LOT WAS ABSORBED AND RECLAIMED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SPILL GENERATED 300 POUNDS OF WASTE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE 170 GALLONS OF RECLAIMED OIL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT MILLIKEN DR. SE, HEBRON OHIO 53025 FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED FOR USING IMPROPER  UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND RECEIVED FOLLOWUP TRAINING ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A DRIVER PLACED A 16 GALLON DRUM OF PETROLEUM NAPTHA ON A DOLLY AND WAS MOVING IT TO HIS TRUCK FOR LOADING WHEN THE DRUM FELL OFF THE DOLLY. WHEN THE DRUM HIT THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT THE LID POPPED OFF AND APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED. THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN UP THE WASTE AND CONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL FOR TRANSPORT. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 90 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS SENT ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN RECYCLING CENTER AT 581 MILLIKEN DR. SE HEBRON, OHIO 53025 FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO USE GREATER CARE WHILE MOVING DRUMS TO AVOID SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A WAREHOUSE FOUND A LEAKING 5 GALLON DRUM IN THE WAREHOUSE DURING AN INSPECTION. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF WASTE HAD LEAKED ONTO  THE FLOOR. THE DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN STRUCK BY FORKLIFT CREATING A SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND RECLAIMED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THIS LEAKING CONTAINER RESULTED IN THE GENERATION OF 100 POUNDS OF WASTE MATERIAL THAT WAS SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN RECYCLING FACILITY AT 633 E 138TH STREET, DOLTON,IL 60419 RECYCLING. WAREHOUSE AT THIS FACILITY WERE COUNSELED TO EXERCISE CARE  WHEN MOVING CONTAINERS WITH A FORKLIFT TO AVOID SIMILAR INCIDENTS.

AFTER THE COMPLETION OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE TWO PLANT WORKERS LEFT TO WASH THEIR HANDS. THEY TOLD THE DRIVER TO WAIT TILL THEY RETURNED. DRIER ACTED INDEPENDENTLY AND STARTED TO DISCONNECT THE CUSTOMER OWNED DELIVERY HOSE FROM HER TANK TRAILER. BACK PRESSURE IN THE HOSE CAUSED AN ESTIMATED ONE-HALF GALLON OF PRODUCT TO BLOW OUT OF THE HOSE WITH  ENOUGH FORCE TO GET INTO DRIVER'S MOUTH AND EYES. PLANT WORKERS TOOK DRIVER TO SAFETY SHOWER, THEN SHE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE CLOSEST HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT OF EYE IRRITATION AND TO BE SURE SHE DID NOT HAVE TOXIC EFFECTS FROM THE PRODUCT IN HER MOUTH. DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM. (OWENSBORO MERCY HEALTH SYSTEM,811 EAST PARRISH AVE, OWENSBORO, KY 42303. THERE ARE NO PERMANENT INJURIES. NO ONE ELSE WAS INJURED, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

CHEMTREC AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE NOTIFIED. MR;. HERMAN NEWELL OF THE ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. THE INSPECTION REVEALED THAT SIX OF THE EIGHT MANWAY EYE BOLTS WERE NOT SECURE. THEY WERE LAYING DOWN. THE OTHER TWO EYE BOLTS WERE IN PLACE, HOWEVER THEY WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT. THE MANWAY COVER COULD BE LIFTED APPROXIMATELY 1/4 INCH OFF THE BASE. THE GASKET WAS IN PLACE AND IN GOOD CONDITION. MR. NEWELL SECURED THE MANWAY BY PROPERLY TIGHTENING ALL EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.

PACKAGE WAS NOTICED DURING THE SORT OPERATION, BECAUSE A SIMILAR BOX FROM THE SAME SHIPPER, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE HAD BEEN QUESTIONED AS BEING AND UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THIS PACKAGE, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR DECLARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  THERE WAS ALSO NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK TO ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  I CONTACTED KATE ZAMPARELLI, BOS REGIONAL COORDINATOR WITH THE FAA, OF THIS SHIPMENT.  PACKAGE HAD NOT MOVED ON ANY AIRCRAFT, AND HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED BY TRUCK TO THIS DESTINATION.  PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DELAY, AND THE MANUFACTURER OF THIS PRODUCT FAXED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AT THIS FACILITY.  PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED FROM THE OTHER PACKAGES, AND THE SPILL CLEANUP PERSON WAS CALLED.  UPON INSPECTION BY THE SPILL CLEANUP PERSON, THE CONTENTS WERE QUESTIONED TO BE A DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER WAS INFORMED OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL, AND AN MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT LABELED, OR MARKED, NOR WAS THERE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK ACCOMPANYING THIS STATEMENT.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES INSIDE THIS BOX WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED AND LEAKED. I CONTACTED KATE ZAMPARELLI WITH THE FAA/BOS REGION COORDINATOR OFFICE, WHO WAS TO HAVE THIS SHIPMENT INVESTIGATED.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT TRAVEL ON AIRCRAFT, AND WAS TRANSPORTED VIA TRUCK.  PACKAGE BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

SUPERVISOR CONTACTED RESPONDER.  RESPONDER ARRIVED ON SCENE WHERE PACKAGE WAS LOCATED.  RESPONDER USED GLOVES AND GOGGLES AND APRON TO PICK-UP AND HANDLE SPILL.  SPILL CLEANED UP AND HANDLED WITHIN PROPER ORDINANCE.  RECOMMENDATION:  ALL PAINT (1) GALLON CANS SHOULD BE ENCASED IN A THICK STYROFOAM SHELL TO GREATLY REDUCES THE SHOCK AND PUNISHMENT THROUGH BASIC SHIPPING AND HANDLING.

column168: I RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL FROM POWER RESOURCES ON NOVEMBER 10, 1998 INDICATING A SMALL LEAK HAD OCCURRED ON TRAILER T-4 AT THE PACKING GLAND OF THE VAPOR SIDE INTERNAL VALVE.  THE LEAK WAS DESCRIBED AS SMALL  ASSOCIATED WITH A FROSTED AREA LOCALIZED ON THE PACKING GLAND.  THEY HAD DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE PACKING GREASE FITTING WAS LEAKING SO THEY APPLIED GREASE.  BUT THEN THE LEAK APPEARED AROUND THE VALVE PACKING.  THE CUSTOMER INDICATED THEY COULD OBTAIN READINGS OF HYDROGEN SULFIDE WITH THEIR DETECTOR ONLY WITHIN A FEW FEET OF THE LEAK.  I DESCRIBED HOW TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING.  AFTER DISCUSSION WITH THE CUSTOMER, TO ASCERTAIN THEIR FAMILIARITY WITH THE VALVE SYSTEM, THE CUSTOMER INDICATED THEY WERE FAMILIAR WITH THE PACKING SYSTEM AND WOULD LOOSEN THE STOP NUT AND PACKING AND APPLY PACKING GREASE WITH A GREASE GUN TO THE PACKING TO STOP THE LEAK AND RETIGHTEN IT AND GET BACK WITH ME IF THERE WAS ANY FURTHER PROBLEM.

THE MSDS INFORMATION INDICATED THAT THE FLASH POINTS FOR THESE WERE BELOW 141 DEGREES F. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND THE PACKAGES WERE HELD PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION. column168: PACKAGE WAS OPENED WHEN NOTICED LEAKING FROM WITHIN. THE CAPS ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE LOOSE AND LEAKED OUT OF THE TOP. AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED ONE FROM THE RECIPIENT AS THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING RETURNED TO THEM BY THE SHIPPER. FLASH POINT WAS NOTED AT 105 DEGREES F. FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND IS BEING HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

HIS PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DAMAGE GOODS AREA BECAUSE OF A "GRAPEFRUIT" ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE AND BECAUSE OF THE LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE JERRICAN. THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS INFORMATION ON THE JERRICAN, EXCEPT THE WORDS "COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID" AND A HAZARDOUS RATE OF "2". NO DANGEROUS GOODS INFORMATION WAS ON THE INTERNATIONAL AIRWAY BILL, BUT THE INNER DRUM WAS MARKED AS COMBUSTIBLE. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER TO GET A MSDS ON THIS MATERIAL. THE FAA DID INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT, AND THE SHIPPER DID FAX A LETTER ON COMPANY LETTERHEAD AND STATED THAT THIS MATERIAL WAS NONHAZARDOUS ACCORDING TO ICAO/IATA REGULATIONS. BECAUSE OF THE DELAYS, THE SHIPPER HAS REQUESTED THAT THIS PACKAGE BE DISPOSED OF ONCE THE FAA RELEASES THE SHIPMENT. FED EX WILL DISPOSE OF THIS THROUGH THE PROPER ENVIRONMENTAL DISPOSAL CHANNELS ONCE THE OFFICIAL FAA RELEASE HAS BEEN GIVEN TO FED EX.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER OVERTURNED VEHICLE AT INTERSECTION OF RT 421& 68 IN GREENSBORO. NC
AFTER UNLOADING USING CT HOSES,DRIVER WAS UNHOOKING AND DROPPED HOSE AND SPILLED PRODUCT.

UPON ARRIVAL AT ECOLAB, THE OVERNITE DRIVER NOTICED MOISTURE AT THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER AS HE PREPARED TO OPEN THE DOOR FOR UNLOADING. THESE WERE FIVE GALLON PAILS STRETCH WRAPPED ON SKIDS WHERE THE PAILS DID NOT COVER THE ENTIRE PALLET SURFACE. THE SKID WERE TIGHT ON THE FLOOR BUT SPACE WAS LEFT BETWEEN THE PRODUCT. TRANSPORTATION CAUSED PAILS TO COLLAPSE WHICH, IN TURN , CAUSED THE SPILL.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 538199 FROM DETROIT WE NOTICED THIS FIBER DRUM HAD LEAKED WE PUT THIS IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND CALLED THE SHIPPER, WHO IS SENDING US ONE OF THEIR RECOVERY DRUMS TO RETURN THE SHIPMENT BACK TO THEM WITH. THIS HAD MAYBE I GALLON LEAK OUT OF IT I CALLED MAX IN SAFETY ABOUT THIS

column168: DRUM WAS LOADED NEXT TO SOME SKIDDED FREIGHT AND APPEARS THAT WHILE THE SKIDDED FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED BY FORKLIFT AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION THE BLADES PUNCTURED THIS DRUM THAT WAS SITTIN IN FRONT OF IT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: A WESTBOUND TRAIN DEPARTING BATTLE CREEK, MICHIGAN, TERMINAL DERAILED AT AN INTERLOCKING NEGOTIATING A CROSSOVER. FOUR CARS INCLUDING TANK CAR GATX 16902 DERAILED IN THE SWITCH. LEADING TRUCKS FROM THE GATX 16902 (A END OF CAR) WERE DISLODGED FROM THE TANK CAR CAUSING THE LEAD END OF THE TANK CAR TO DROP TO THE RAILS. AS A RESULT, THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND VALVE HANDLE WERE SHEARED FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE OUTLET VALVE ABOVE THE SHEAR PLATE SADDLE UNSEATED TO ALLOW DRIPPING TO OCCUR AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 DROPS PER SECOND. RAILROAD EMERGENCY RESPONDER AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT BLOCKED OUTLET VALVE TO CONTROL DRIPPING. DURING THE DERAILMENT A SUPPLY LINE OF NATURAL GAS USED TO FUEL SWITCH SNOW HEATERS WAS SEVERED ABOVE GROUND CAUSING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO EVACIATE APPROXIMATELY 25 PERSONS IN BUILDINGS ADJACENT TO RIGHT OF WAY FOR A TWO (2) HOUR PERIOD UNTIL THE GAS LINE COULD BE CAPPED. AFTER TANK CAR WAS RERAILED, IT WAS MOVED BACK TO THE YARD APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) MILE AND PLACED ON AN ISOLATION TRACK WHERE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR.

DRUM WAS FATIGED FROM CORROSISION AND STRESSED  DURING TRANSPORT DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND TRAILER DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED AND RETRAINED TO LOOK FOR OLD AND FATIGED DRUMS. INSTUCTED TO REJECT SUCH DRUMS IN THE FUTURE.

DOCKMAN ALERTED ME THAT A PEICE OF FREIGHT HAD DROPPED FROM FORKLIFT AND PUNCTURED BOTH DRUMS CAUSING THEM TO LEAK THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. 1ST CALLED HOME OFFICE, TALKED TO EDDIE YANCE ON WHAT TO DO. 2ND CALLED PUT OIL DRY ON GROUND UNDER TRAILER TO CONTAIN SPILL, ALSO PUT A DRUM TO CATCH MATERIAL IN. 3RD CALL CHEMTREC, THEY SENT MSD. 4TH GAVE DIRECTIONS TO TERMINAL, TO CARE, CARE CONTACTED A CLEAN-UP AGENCY.

AT 16:35 WE NOTICED THAT THE TANK WAS LEAKING WHEN WE MOVED IT FROM ITS RESTED LOCATION TO THE MIDDLE OF THE DOCK TO LOAD IT OUT. THIS WAS ON THE 23RD OF NOVEMBER. THERE WAS A SMALL PUDDLE OF FLUID ON THE DOCK UNDER WHERE THE TANK WAS RESTED AT IN THE OS&D LOCATION. WE THEN STATRED TO CALL ALL THE EMERGENCY PERSONNELL (OPE,HM RELEASE HOTLINE, CHIP MCLENDON (OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR). WE WERE INFORMED TO CLEAN IT UP AND PLACE DEPREA IN A SALVAGE DRUM.
Upon unloading trailer, NNC DSR, Ken Youngblood punctured kit. It was cleaned up and contained in a drum.

The driver was at the loading site. The product overflowed due to inaccurate settings by the operator. This caused a 200 gallon spill of jet fuel. The spill was contained and cleaned up by the operator. The driver was not at fault. The product flowed into a drain and into a holding tank.
Driver discovered a broken bag at receiver's. Receiver accepted all product while the driver went to JB Hunt facility for trailer clean up.

Driver opened valve on product line prior to hooking hose to the unloading line. Vapor release occurred. Product dissipated into the atmosphere and there was no clean up required. Driver was aware that he should not have opened the valve prior to making the connection. There were no injuries and no product reached any waterways.

column168: Upon opening his vehicle to unload, a driver discovered that one of the cargo straps securing his load came loose, allowing a five gallon drum to fall over. Approximately one half gallon of material leaked from the drum into the back of the truck. The driver used absorbent pads to clean up the spill and placed the pads into an overpack. This spill generated five pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the Safety-Kleen facility at 1722 Cooper Creek Rd., Denton, TX 76208 for recycling. The driver was counseled to make sure on future shipments that all straps are secure.

A pallet failed at a temporary storage facility allowing several 16 gallon drums to fall onto the floor. One of the drum lids popped loose allowing two gallons of material to spill. A warehouse man absorbed the spill with pads and secured the lid back on the container. The used absorbent pads were placed into an overpack and stored at the facility. This spill generated approximately 20 pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the Safety Kleen facility at 581 Milliken Drive S.E., Hebron OH 43025 for recycling. The warehouse men at this facility were briefed to closely inspect pallets for defects prior to using them to avoid similar incidents.

A warehouse man discovered that one of the 55 gallon drums in temporary storage had a pinhole leak. Approximately one gallon of waste leaked into a secondary containment at the transfer facility. The leaking drum was overpacked and the spilled material was absorbed with pads and also placed into an overpack. This leaker produced approximately ten pounds of waste that was transported to the Safety-Kleen facility at 1200 Sylvan Street, Linden, NJ 07036, along with the original waste  for recycling. The warehouse men were instructed to closely inspect incoming drums to locate leakers sooner.

A driver heard a drum fall over in the back of his truck as he was pulling into the West Brookfield Safety-Kleen facility. A 16 gallon fiber drum fell in the back of his truck, the lid popped off spilling the entire contents of the drum into the trailer. The driver contacted an emergency response contractor that responded and cleaned up the spilled material into overpacks. This spill generated approximately 200 pounds of waste that was transported along with the original shipment, to the Safety-Kleen facility at 1200 Sylvan St., Linden, NJ 07036, for recycling. The driver was counseled to exercise greater care in securing drums that are being transported in his truck.

column168: The transport vehicle was proceeding through Memorial Circle in Augusta, Maine. The driver hit the inside curb of this rotary and lost control of the vehicle. The vehicle rolled onto its side and struck the granite curb on the outside of the rotary. The impact with the curb caused the tube of the trailer to rupture. Crews with gravel diked as much of the oil as possible. Product also went into the nearby sewer. This product was contained at the sewerage treatment plant. The tanker was carrying 9000 gallons of #6 oil. Approximately 1800 gallons was left in the tanker. This product was pumped into another tank and taken to its destination. Approximately 5500 gallons went into the storm drains and were subsequently contained in the sewerage treatment plant. This oil was pumped out of the plant and disposed of by clean harbors environmental company. The balance of the oil was absorbed by the sand spread on the spill and subsequently transported to Dragon Products, located in Thomaston, ME.

column168: NATX33006, NOVEMBER 9, 1998, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 2315 HOURS, MONDAY, NOVEMBER 9, 1998 AT CONRAIL'S HARRINGTON YARD IN HARRINGON, DELAWARE, CONRAIL CAR INSPECTORS NOTED AN ODOR AROUND LOADED TANK CAR NATX33006 CONTAINING BUTADIENE, INHIBITED. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. FURTHER INSPECTIONS BY CSX/CONRAIL DIRECTOR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SYSTEMS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER AND REPRESENTATIVES OF H.M.H.T..C. ( CONTRACTOR REQUESTED VIA SHIPPER), FOUND ODOR ORIGINATING INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA. MONITORING BY CONTRACTOR REVEAL ONLY 6 PPM WHEN SAMPLED INSIDE HOUSING WITH COVER CLOSED. WHEN COVER WAS OPENED, NO READINGS WERE DETECTED. THERE WERE INTERMITTENT AREAS ON THE GROUND LEVEL, HOWEVER, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED. ALL VALVES AND FITTING INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WERE INSPECTED AND NO EXCEPTIONS NOTED. A FAINT "CLATTER" WAS NOTED TO SEEMINGLY, ORIGINATE FROM INSIDE THE CAR UNDER THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. ALL VALVES WERE LEAK TESTED WITH A SOAP SOLUTION BUT DID NOT REVEAL A SOURCE. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CUSTOMER REICHHOLD CHEMICAL, WHO ALSO PHYSICALLY INSPECTED THE CAR AT THE INITIAL TIME INCIDENT WAS REPORTED, ALSO TOOK NO EXCEPTION. THE TANK CAR WAS BEING FORWARDED TO A PRIVATE SHOP FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. THE CAUSE IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.

DRIVER STARTED PUMPING, UNLOADER CAME OUT AND TOLD HIM NOTHING WAS GOING INTO STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER SAID HIS HOSE WAS FULL SO THEY MUST HAVE A VALVE CLOSED. THE UNLOADER TOLD THE DRIVER EVERYTHING WAS OPEN AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO DISCONNECT FROM THE PIPE AND CHECK. THE DRIVER TOLD HIMM TO START HIS PUMP TO RELIEVE ANY PRESSURE AND THE UNLOADER SAID THERE WASN'T ANY. HE AGAIN TOLD THE DRIVER TO DISCONNECT AND WHEN HE DID, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OR PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT AND SOME GOT ON OUR DRIVER AND IN HIS EYES. THE PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED THE DRIVER OFF AND DIRT ON THE SPILL THEN SHOVELED UP FOR DISPOSAL.

OPENED LIQUID VALVE, UTLX 80035, NOVEMBER 25, 1998, ALBANY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0704 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 25, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S WEST SPRINGFIELD YARD IN WEST SPRINGFIELD, MA, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 80035 CONTAINING ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0815 HOURS, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM PRAXAIR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT HAD AN OPEN LIQUID VALVE.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY PRAXAIR WHO CLOSED THE LIQUID VALVE.  APPROXIMATELY 0820 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

DURING UNLOADING, A DRUM OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DUE TO A CRACKED BOTTOM SEAM.  APPROXIMATELY SEVEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE DAMAGED DRUM.  ULTIMATELY, THE DRUM WAS ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER AND OUR TRAILER CLEANED OF ALL RESIDUE.

column168: DRIVER WAS TURNING LEFT ONTO A FRONTAGE ROAD PULLING TWO AMMONIA WAGONS. AS HE TURNED, THE FIRST AMMONIA WAGON ROLLED OVER INTO A DITCH.  THE ROLL CAUSED A VALVE TO OPEN BUT DID NOT BREAK THE VALVE. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE SINCE IT WAS NOT BROKEN AND STOP THE AMMONIA RELEASE.  THE AMMONIA THAT REMAINED IN THE TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN EMPTY ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK.  THE SECOND NURSE TANK REMAINED UPRIGHT.  APPROXIMATELY 1470 POUNDS OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASE.  AFTER SOIL SAMPLES WAS TAKEN, THE 57-FOOT AREA SURROUNDING THE SPILL WAS EXCAVATED.  ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO A NEARBY FIELD.  THE WAGON WHICH ROLLED WAS AN OLDER DESIGN THAT CARRIED THE TANK HIGHER THAN MOST WAGONS.  DUE TO THE WAGON DESIGN, THE TANK WAS REMOVED  FROM SERVICE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRACTOR PUMP HAS THE CAPABILITY TO BE USED ON EITHER SIDE WITH THE USE OF A VALVE.  WHEN PUMPING FROM THE DIVERS SIDE, A VALVE IS OPENED TO ALLOW SORBENT TO FLOW TO THAT SIDE.  AT THE SAME TIME PRESSURE BUILDS UP ON PASSENGER SIDE.  THE PRESSURE OF THE SORBENT BEING PUMPED FORCED THE CAP OFF.  OUR DRIVE NOTICED THE FLOW OF SORBENT IMMEDIATELY AND SHUT OFF THE PUMP,  CLOSED ALL THE VALVES AND CONTAINED THE SORBENT WITH FLOOR DRY.  THE FLOOR DRY WAS THAN SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUMS AND WILL BE SHIPPED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  VALVES WILL BE RE-PLACED ON BOTH SIDES TO ELIMINATE THIS PROBLEM AS WELL AS LOCKING COVERS A THE MALE FITTINGS SHOULD A VALVE FAIL.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 11, 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 1:15 AM, CP TRAIN NO. 428-11 DERAILED 40 CARS JUST EAST OF ANA MOOSE, ND., THREE OF THE CARS WERE TANK CARS OF STYRENE MONOMER, INHIBITED, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN-2055, PG111.  ONE OF THE TANK CARS, PROX 23065, WAS DISCOVERED ON ITS SIDE AND LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF STYRENE MONOMER FROM ITS VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS WEDGED TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CONTENTS OF ALL THREE TANKS CARS WAS TRANSFERRED INTO 15 TANK TRUCKS AND RUBBERED TO DESTINATION.  THE FOUR PEOPLE EVACUATED FROM THEIR RESIDENTS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN HOME AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED .  THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION CLEAN UP REQUIRED IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: UNIT SOUTHBOUND ON US 167 NEAR LINCOLN/JACKSON PARISH (COUNTY) LINE. ROADWAY IS TWO LANE UNDIVIDED IN GOOD REPAIR.  DRIVER APPROACHED DOWNGRADE ENTERING RIGHT TURN TO BRIDGE SPANNING SHEPPARD CREEK. DUE TO DRIVER CONDITION, HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO OBTAIN STATEMENT AT THIS WRITING.  IT IS SPECULATED THAT DRIVER DRIFTED ACROSS CENTERLINE OF ROADWAY, AND ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT.  IN DOING SO, LOAD SHIFTED, PRODUCT WEIGHT IS APPROXIMATELY 10.75 POUNDS PER GALLON, CAUSING CENTER OF GRAVITY TO MOVE.  UNIT BEGAN TO OVERTURN ONTO DRIVER SIDE.  AS UNIT WAS IN PARTIAL OVERTURNED JACK-KNIFE POSITION, COMBINATION STRUCK CONCRETE BRIDGE ABUTMENT AFTER DESTROYING STEEL AND TIMBER IMPACT ATTENUATOR.  DRIVER TOTALLY EJECTED FROM CAB OF UNIT WHILE STILL SECURED BY PASSIVE RESTRAINT SYSTEM.  SEAT ASSEMBLY WAS TORN FROM FLOORBOARD OF CAB.  DRIVER AIRBORNE FOR SOME 54' TO POINT OF IMPACT ON GROUND ON OPPOSING SIDE OF CREEK.  UNIT CAME TO REST OVERTURNED AND PARTIALLY SUBMERGED IN CREEK.  STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF VESSEL WAS BREACHED AT NOSE SEAM, LOWER AREA BETWEEN 6 AND 9 O'CLOCK AREA ON DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY 2600 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LOST INTO CREEK.  REMEDIATION EFFORTS UNDER SUPERVISION OF LA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  WORK WAS COMPLETED AND APPROVED ON TUESDAY, DECEMBER 1, 1998.  DRIVER REMAINS HOSPITALIZED WITH SERIOUS INJURIES.

column168: When our driver started to unload the mid-grade gasoline into the underground storage tank, the in-line 90% full shut-off flapper closed. This abrupt stop caused the unloading hose and the coaxial adaptor to move, thus loosening the pop off connector. The driver immediately shut off the flow, however, about 37 gallons spilled onto the asphalt parking lot and down into the sewer. The Gurnee Fire Department came and flushed down the parking lot, causing gasoline residue to be placed into the creek (drainage ditch) about two blocks away. S.E.T. Environmental was on the scene, cleaning the sewer system and creek.

AS THE 10 PIECES IN THE SHIPMENT HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING AND LABELING NOR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  I WAS ABLE TO OBTAIN MSDS'S FROM THE MANUFACTURERS ON THREE PRODUCTS, THE DOW CLEANER WHICH LISTS A FLASH POINT OF MINUS 20 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT, THE LYSOL DISINFECTANT SPRAY WITH A FLASH POINT OF 73 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT AND THE NIAGARA SPRAY STARCH WHICH WAS NOT FLAMMABLE ACCORDING TO THE MSDS.  THE DOW CLEANER AND THE LYSOL DISINFECTANT CLEANER IS BELIEVED TO BE AEROSOL, FLAMMABLE NOS AND THE OTHERS ARE BELIEVED TO AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE NOS.  FAA AGENT TONY DGUYEN WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING THIS INVESTIGATION. ALTHOUGH THE SHIPPER ADDRESS WAS LISTED AS IN CA, THE PACKAGE WAS ACTUALLY SHIPPED FROM VIRGINIA BEACH, VA.

ON 11/2/1998 AT 2:45 P.M. RICK DUNN (SERVICE DISPATCHER) WAS NOTIFIED BY TROY KONNICK (TRANSPORT DRIVER)  THAT THERE WAS A BROKEN PIPE IN THE BULK PLANT. AT THIS TIME I HAD GLEN WILLIAMS LOAD OIL DRY AND SPILL KIT ON # 330 TO MEET US AT BULT PLANT. MEANWHILE RICK DUNN, DOMENIC VECCIONE, TROY KONNICK, AND I (BOB TODER) RAN TO THE BILK PLANT TO EVALUATE THE PROBLEM. AT THIS POINT WE FOUND THE PUMP IN THE OFF POSITION, BUT THERE WAS KERO SPRAYING FROM THE PUMP. I THEN CLOSED BOTH ISOLATING VALVES ON INLET AND OUTLET SIDES OF THE TANK VALVES ( TANK #461), WE THEN BEGAN TO STOP FLOW OF KERO WITH THE USE OF OIL DRY, ABSORBENT PADS, ETC. I THEN HAD RICK DUNN STICK THE TANK #461 TO DETERMINE THE AMOUNT OF OIL RELEASED. AFTER CALCULATING THE STICK READING TO THE A.M. INVENTORY, WE DETERMINED WE HAD LOST APPROXIMATELY 600 GALLON. WE THEN NOTIFIED KEN LONGACRE, JR., AND BRUCE LIMBERT WHO THEN NOTIFIED THE D.E.P., AND J&J SPILL, WE THEN PROCEEDED TO CHECK THE STEAM LOCATED ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE BULK PLANT. AT THIS TIME WE FOUND NO SIGN OF PRODUCT RELEASED INTO THE CREEK. WE THEN STARTED TO SET UP DAMS AT THREE LOCATIONS, JUST IN THE EVENT THE PRODUCT WOULD BE RELEASED INTO  THIS AREA. ONCE THIS WAS DONE, RICK COLEMAN, KEN LONGACRE, JR., AND J&J SPILL ARRIVED. J&J SPILL THEN DECIDED TO SET UP TWO ADDITIONAL DAMS TO SECURE AND POSSIBLE RELEASE. AFTER EVERY STEP AND PRECAUTION WAS TAKEN, WE THEN RECHECKED OUR FIGURES TO MAKE SURE HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS LOST AND CAME TO A CALCULATION OF 1,091 GALLONS TOTAL LOSS. AT 9:30 P.M. DOMENIC  VECCIONE CAME BACK TO THE SHOP TO CHECK ALL AREAS IN THE CREEK TO ASSURE WE DID NOT NEED TO TAKE ANY ADDITIONAL ACTIONS AT THIS TIME. NOTHING WAS FOUND SO WE CONTINUED TO MONITOR THE SITUATION SHOWN ON THE SCHEDULE BELOW. WE CONTINUED TO MONITOR THE CREEK ON A DAILY BASIS. ON 11/5/1998 J&J SPILL BEGAN TO REMOVE THE SOIL AND ON 11/9/1998 THEY COMPLETED REMOVAL OF SOIL FROM AROUND PUMP.

column168: THIS IS UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.  ON 11/7/98 A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" BUILDING AND "B" BUILDING SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN.  ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL HE DISCOVERED A VERY STRONG ODOR OF VINEGAR. THIS ODOR WAS BEING REPORTED IN DIFFERENT SECTIONS OF "A" BUILDING & "B" BUILDING.  ALAN HENDERSON MADE THE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS TO THE DISPATCHED AREA AND HIS SUPERVISOR (KAREN SCHATZMANN).  SPILL TEAMS WERE DISPATCHED TO BOTH BUILDINGS. THE  AREAS OF "A" BUILDING AND "B" WERE EVACUATED AT THIS TIME, APPROXIMATELY 100 PEOPLE.  THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY (3) EMPLOYEES REPORTING SYMPTOMS OF IRRIATION TO THE RESPIRATORY TRACT. THESE EMPLOYEES WERE INSTRUCTED TO FILL OUT ACCIDENT REPORTS AND SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION IF SYMPTOMS PERSISTED.  THE BUILDINGS WERE OPENED UP TO VENTILATE.  THE ODOR DISSIPATED IN "A" BUILDING BUT STILL PRESENT IN "B" BUILDING.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FINALLY FOUND IN OUR "B" BUILDING ON THE BOTTOM FLOOR.  UPON ARRIVAL ALAN HENDERSON DISCOVERED A STYROFOAM COOLER HAD A LIBRA LABEL ATTACHED AND A INTER DC TRANSFER PAPER.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 6 X 1.06 PINT, GLASS RECEPTACLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THE RECEPTACLES WERE MARKED, ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL, UN2790.  THESE RECEPTACLES WERE PACKED IN STYRAFOAM PEANUTS.  THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT.  THE INSPECTION FOUND 1 OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES TO BE BROKEN, LEAKING CONTENTS ON THE INSIDE OF THE COOLER ONLY.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS ON THE OUTER COOLER TO INDICATE THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR AND WAS HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. BELOW IS A BREAK DOWN OF THE COSTS FOR THIS INCIDENT.  COSTS: STAFFING $98.00, 1 RECOVERY DRUM $60.00, BAGS & TOWELS $10.00

column14: FREEMAN AVE/ ON RAMP TO I-464
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: COMPANY DRIVER (GILBERT) STATES: AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION LIGHT AT WHICH HE WAS GOING TO MAKE A LEFT HAD TURN ONTO 1-464 SOUTH ON-RAMP, IT WAS GREEN TO THROUGH TRAFFIC.  BEFORE REACHING THE LIGHT, THE LEFT HAND TURN LANE LIGHT TURNED GREEN, GIVING HIM RIGHT OF WAY FOR HIS TURN.  HE STATES THAT HE SAW HEADLIGHTS COMING TOWARD HIM IN OPPOSITE DIRECTION BUT PROCEEDED WITH HIS TURN, AS HE HAD RIGHT OF WAY.  HE STATES THAT HE HAD NO REASON TO THINK THAT THE UNIDENTIFIED VEHICLE WAS SPEEDING OR WAS ENTERING THE ON RAMP, AS IT APPEARED TO BE IN CENTER LANE OF ROADWAY, NOT IN RIGHT HAND TURN LANE.  DRIVER STATES HE WAS GRADUALLY BRAKING THROUGHOUT TURN. UPON ENTERING THE ON-RAMP, COMPANY DRIVER STATES HE WAS CUT OFF BY THE LATE MODEL WHITE PICK UP TRUCK THAT APPARENTLY ENTERED THE ON-RAMP WITHOUT OBEYING THE YIELD SIGN.  IN AN EFFORT TO AVOID IMPACT, COMPANY DRIVER STATES THAT HE TURNED THE WHEEL HARD TO THE LEFT, CAUSING LOAD IN TRAILER TO SHIFT.  HE THEN TRIED TO CORRECT BY TURNING WHEEL GRADUALLY TO THE RIGHT, BUT WAS UNABLE TO CONTROL TRACTOR TRAILER BEFORE IT WENT INTO A SLOW ROLLOVER ONTO SHOULDER OF ROADWAY.  COMPANY DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS IN SIXTH GEAR INTO THE TURN, WHICH IS THE LAST POSSIBLE GEAR IN LOW RANGE. THE APPROXIMATE MAXIMUM SPEED FOR THIS GEAR IS 15 MPH.  HE ALSO STATES THAT HE NEVER APPLIED THE BRAKES HARD AND THAT THE VEHICLE NEVER SLID. THE SPEED LIMIT ON FREEMAN AVENUE IS 35 MPH DIVIDED TWO LANE ROADWAY.  AT THE INTERSECTIONS TO THE ON-RAMP TRAFFIC IS CONTROLLED BY A SIGNAL LIGHT AND YIELD SIGNS INCLUDING ARROWS GIVING RIGHT OF WAY TO LEFT TURNS ONTO THE ON-RAMP.  SKID MARKS AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT DO NOT APPEAR TO BELONG TO COMPANY VEHICLE AS THEY EXTEND PAST THE AREA IN WHICH THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST.  THE TANKER WAS LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL, OF WHICH, APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO SHOULDER OF ROADWAY. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE (IMS: ANTHONY KEELING, SUPERVISOR,  PHONE 757-543-5718) CONTACTED TO REMEDIATE SPILL SITE.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON NOVEMBER 23, 0998, AWA RAMP PERSONNEL AT MCCARRAN INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (LAS), DISCOVERED A WHEELCHAIR RESTING ON ITS DIE IN THE REAR CARGO HOLD OF FLIGHT 735.  BATTERY ACID HAD LEAKED ONTO THE CARGO BIN FLOOR AND A FEW NEARBY BAGS.  HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED OUT TO CLEAN THE WHEELCHAIR, PASSENGER BAGS AND CARGO BIN.  EFFORTS INITIATED TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE: EMPLOYEES INVOLVED HAVE BEEN DISCIPLINED AND HAVE RECEIVED ADDITIONAL HANDS ON CLASSROOM INSTRUCTION IN ELECTRIC WHEELCHAIR HANDLING PROCEDURES. ADDITIONALLY, AWA HAS PREPARED A REVISION TO THE GROUND OPERATIONS MANUAL, WHICH ADDS WARNINGS AND VISUAL AIDS TO ASSIST IN IDENTIFYING BATTERY TYPES.  MANAGERS WILL BE REQUIRED TO BRIEF STATION PERSONNEL WHEN THE REVISION IS DISTRIBUTED LATER IN THE MONTH.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER, JAMES KNUTSON, LEFT THE FLYING J TRUCKSTOP AT BEACH, NORTH DAKOTA IN THE MORNING, HE PROCEEDED TO ENTER THE FREEWAY.  AS HE WENT ACROSS THE BRIDGE, HE MADE A SHARP LEFT FOR THE ACCESS RAMP. AFTER THE LEFT TURN WAS MADE, HE FELT THE TRAILER COME OFF THE GROUND.  BOTH TRACTOR AND TRAILER ENDED UP ON THEIR SIDES.  JAMES HAD ON A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LOAD.  THE TOTES WERE LOADED AS FOLLOWING:  FRONT (AN DRAWING OF THE SITUATION/ARRANGEMENT).  AS THE TRAILER WENT OVER, THE END LEFT TOTE FELL ON TOP OF THE RIGHT ONE CAUSING IT TO BURST AND SPILL THE CONTENTS OF AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE/AMMONIUM CHLORIDE.  ONLY ONE TOTE WAS DAMAGED.  CLEAN UP CREWS FROM BEACH, ND PERFORMED DECONTAMINATION AND CLEAN UP PROCEDURES. THE CAUSE OF THE CRASH WAS DETERMINED AS SPEED TOO FAST FOR THE LAYOUT OF THE ACCESS RAMP.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED  DUE TO SERIOUS DISREGARD OF SAFETY AND COMPANY POLICY VIOLATION.

column168: AB12398D, SHIPPER LAB CORP OF AMERICA, AWB#MAF 389039707 EGE, THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. 03:19, 11/18/98, A SPILL EMITTING AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN  B BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DIANE RAMSDEN AND DONNA RESOR DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES, NOMEX SUITS AND RESPONDED TOT HE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THE LEAKAGE ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX HAD DRIED AND TURNED INTO A STAIN. NO PH TEST WAS OBTAINED FROM THE OUTER PACKAGING.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND, CLOTHES, CANDLES, AND EMPTY DECORATIVE GLASS BOTTLE, AND MARBLE ROLLING PIN AND 1-10 OUNCE METAL AEROSOL CAN OF HONCHOS BOOT SPRAY.  THE OUTER PLASTIC CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURED ONTO HE METAL AEROSOL CAN AND WAS DETACHED FROM THE CAN DURING TRANSPORT CAUSING THE SPRAY NOZZLE TO DEPLOY TWO OUNCES OF THE BOOT SPRAY.   THEY RESEAL THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED IT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKING LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATER. ALL AREAS INVOLVED IN THIS SPILL WERE CLEANED AND VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  CLEAR OF SCENE 03:43.

column168: UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, MARK REIMERS WAS NOTIFIED AT 1633 HRS. ON 11/12/98 BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER (RMCC), THAT CONTAINER MOGU 209484 ON UP TRAIN ILADU 09 WAS LEAKING IN THE AMOURDALE YARD. NO PLACARDS WERE DISPLAYED ON THE CONTAINER, HOWEVER EXAMINATION OF THE BILL OF LADING FOUND ON THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE DRUMS OF PESTICIDE. MR. REIMER REQUESTED THAT UNION PACIFIC ENVIRONMENTAL MANGER, CHRISTI HORNICK BE NOTIFIED AND RESPOND UNTIL MR. REIMERS COULD ARRIVE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, CHEMTREC, THE STATE OF KANSAS, THE DEPT. OF EMERGENCY MGMT., AND THE KANSAS CORPORATE COMMISSION WERE NOTIFIED. CHEMTREC WAS UNABLE TO CONTACT MATSUI, AS ALL OF THE NUMBERS THEY HAD LISTED ROLLED TO PHONE MAIL. CHEMTREC WAS ABLE TO NOTIFY PAT MCGORTY, A REPRESENTATIVE FOR THE CONSIGNEE WHO CONTACTED THE RMCC. THE RMCC PATCHED MR. REIMERS IN WITH MR. MCGORTY. AT MR. REIMERS REQUEST, MR. MCGORTY FAXED COPIES OF THE MSDS'S FOR THE CHEMICAL. MS HORNICK ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS HAD BEEN RELEASED. PRIOR TO MR. REIMERS ARRIVAL, THE CONTAINER WAS GROUNDED, AND OPENED BY MS. HORNICK AND REPRESENTATIVES FROM OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALISTS, INC. MS. HORNICK AND THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO TRANSLOAD THE DRUMS INTO A CLEAN CONTAINER AFER CONTAMINATING EACH DRUM WITH A BLEACH SOLUTION. THE DECONTAMINATED DRUMS WERE LOADED NTO INTERMODAL CONTAINER SP.L MR REIMERS PROPERLY PLACARDED THE NEW CONTAINER UPON HIS ARRIVAL. BLOCKING AND BRACING OF THE LOAD CONSISTED OF 2-4X4 'S WEDGED PERPENDICULARLY TO THE DRUMS ACROSS THE WIDTH OF THE CONTAINER. 3- 1X4'S WERE NAILED VERTICALLY TO THE 4X4'S. NO FOOT BOARDS OR KNEE BRACES WERE USED. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LOAD SHIFTING. EXAMINATION OF EACH DRUM DISCLOSED THAT THE DRUMS WERE OLD, RUSTY NONSPECIFICATION DRUMS THAT HAD BEEN FRESHLY PAINTED WITH BLACK PAINT. THE DRUMS WERE MARKED APPROPRIATELY. THE PAINT WOULD NOT ADHERE TO THE RUST, AND AS A RESULT MUCH OF THE PAINT HAD FLAKED OFF EN ROUTE. ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD RUSTED THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, RESULTING IN THE TOTAL RELEASE OF THE 55 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. ADDITIONALLY, 10 OTHER DRUMS WERE SEEPING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE BUNGS. CLOSER EXAMINATION REVEALED A LACK OF GASKETS ON THE BUNG CAPS. AT THIS POINT, THE SPILL ESTIMATE WAS REVISED TO 60 GALLONS. BESIDES THE CONTAMINATED MOGU CONTAINER, SEVERAL CONTAINERS AND ONE INTERMODAL CAR THAT WERE ADJACENT TO THE LEAKING CONTAINER WERE CONTAMINATED WITH THE PRODUCT. EACH OF THESE CONTAINERS AND THE CAR WERE DECONTAMINATED BEFORE BEING ALLOWED BACK IN TRANSPORTATION. MITSUI ASKED THAT THE CONTAINER TRANSPORTING THE DRUMS BE HELD UNTIL SUCH TIME AS THE CONSIGNEE AGREED TO ACCEPT SHIPMENT. AT THAT TIME, THE CONTAINER WILL CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION VIA HIGHWAY.KAY A HOUFEK

column168: AT 1635 HOURS ON 11/23/1998, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, TERRY BOUDREAUX WAS ADVISED THAT THE WESTWEGO YARD SWITCH CREW YWG54 23 FOUND TANK CAR ACFX89857 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  BOUDREAUX INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING AT ABOUT ONE GALLON PER MINUTE.  HE DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH REG MGR MIKE SEABOUGH.  SEABOUGH ADVISED THAT HE WOULD CONTACT RMCC AND REQUEST THEY CONTACT THE NECESSARY EMERGENCY EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND A CONTRACTOR CET ENVIRONMENTAL.  BOUDREAUX CONTACTED YARDMASTER AND INSTRUCTED HIM TO CEASE ANY TRAIN MOVEMENT IN TEH WESTWEGO YARD.  AT 1740 HOURS WESTWEGO FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT SPECIALIST KENNY BOUVIER ARRIVED AND SURVEYED THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  AT 1850 HRS LOUISIANA STATE POLICE TROOPER MELVIN REIN ARRIVED.  TOGETHER, THEY CONTACTED METHANEX METHANOL COMPANY'S JERRY DUFRENSE IN CANADA AND ADVISED HOM OF THE INCIDENT.  THEY ALSO NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN LOADED BY CYTEC OF AVONDALE, LA. AND CONTACTED PAUL MINET OF CYTEC RESPONSE TEAM.  HE ADVISED THAT HE WOULD RESPOND.  AT 1950 HRS CET ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED WITH CRAIG GREER AND SUBMITTED A SAFETY PLAN AFTER SURVEYING THE INCIDENT.  WITH PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND AIR PACKS CET REPAIRED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THEY FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE WAS DEFECTIVE AND THE BUTTERFLY VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED.  THEY ALSO FOUND THAT THE GASKET IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS DEFECTIVE.  THEY CLOSED THE OUTLET VALVE PROPERLY AND REPLACED THE GASKET IN THE VALVE CAP.  SEAL UNION PACIFIC F-482849 WAS PLACED ON THE BOTTOM OPERATING VALVE HANDLE.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED BY ALTON AND SOUTHERN RR THAT TANK CAR CELX11224 WAS EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE A&S RR YARD AT EAST STY.  LOUIS MANAGER TUFTS NOTIFIED REGIONAL MANAGER MIKE SEABAUGH AND RMCC DISPATCHER. HE RESPONDED TO THE YARD, NOTING UPON ARRIVAL THAT THERE WAS VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND THAT THE LIQUID AND AIR VALVE PLUG WERE LOOSE. THE LIQUID AND AIR VALVE PLUGS WERE TIGHTENED BY MECHANICAL SUP. RICHARD WULF AND THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS NOTED TO CONTINUE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. MANAGER TUFTS DISASSEMBLED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HOUSE AFTER DETERMINING THAT THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 15 LBS OF PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND EXPOSED THE O RING WERE INVERTED AND THE VALVE REASSEMBLED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED ACTIONS TAKEN REQUESTING THAT THE CAR BE SHOPPED FOR FULL INSPECTION AND REPAIRS UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION.

REGIONAL MANAGER DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS RICHARD GREEN, SPARKS, NV., THAT NEVADA PUC HAD REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX66138 LEAKING IN THE AREA OF THE HINGED MANWAY COVER LID. INSPECTION FOUND HINGED MANWAY COVER LID PROTECTED BY INTACT SEAL CAUSTIC 1933. INSPECTION FOUND MANWAY GASKET CRACKED AND MISALIGNED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED FROM TANK CAR DOWN MANWAY NOZZLE AND SIDE OF TANK CAR. CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION WAS MADE BY RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, ST. LOUIS, MO., RESULTED IN BOB THIES, ELF ATOCHEM, PORTLAND, OR., CALLING WHITELEY SO REPLACEMENT GASKET COULD BE OBTAINED. GASKET WAS RECEIVED ON DECEMBER 3, 1998, CAR WAS REPAIRED AND RELEASED FROM BAD ORDER STATUS. NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED. SEAL UPF 329835 WAS APPLIED MANWAY COVER LID. SEAL CAUSTIC 1934 WAS REMOVED FROM COMBINATION COVER TO ALLOW INSPECTION OF SECUREMENT OF PLUGS IN AIR AND LIQUID VALVES. SEAL UPF329834 WAS APPLIED FOR PROTECTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP BY THE WEST END SWITCH CREW DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO YERMO YARD, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BLOWN FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND STYLE MOUNTED ADJACENT TO THE MIDWAY, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REMOVED.  IT WAS REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE ZOOK 165 POUND DISC, AND REASSEMBLED.  IT APPEARED THE CAR HAD BEEN ROUGH HANDLED IN TRANSIT CAUSING THE LIQUID TO SURGE THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR INFORMATION.

column168: WHILE PERFORMING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, REGIONAL MGR MARK REIMERS NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE CAR HAD A BAD MANWAY COVER GASKET AND 6 LOOSE SWING BOLTS.  REG. MGR. REIMERS REPLACED THE GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE SWING BOLTS AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ADVISING HIM OF THE PROBLEM.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE ROADWAY 805 SECTION, STALL NUMBER 147.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED TOXIC, THE AREA WAS SECURED TO PREVENT THROUGH TRAFFIC AND ISOLATED, PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND NOTED A SMALL POOL (LESS THAN 1 PINT) OF LIQUID ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE RIGHT FRONT NOSE OF THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER.  A SLIGHT ODOR OF TDI WAS PREVALENT IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE SPILL.  THE CORNER OF THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT, AND THEN MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK, WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED.  THE PAVEMENT IN THE STALL AREA WAS COVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND ISOLATED PENDING REMEDIATION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LADING OF DOUBLE STACKED METAL DRUMS WAS SECURED WITH TY-GARD FABRIC MATERIALS.  THE DRUMS WERE SEPARATED ON THE BILEVEL WITH 1/2 INCH PLYWOOD.  THE TY-GARD APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PROPERLY APPLIED EXCEPT FOR THE SIDEWALL APPLICATION WHERE THE FABRIC WAS ONLY ATTACHED TO THE RAISED PORTIONS IN THE CORRUGATED SIDEWALLS, AND DID NOT FOLLOW THE OUTWARD PORTIONS OF THE CORRUGATION.  WHILE THE TY-GARD APPEARED TO HAVE "STRETCHED" SOME, THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY NOTICEABLE DAMAGE TO THE DRUMS FROM MOVING WHILE IN TRANSIT.  INFORMATION FROM THE DRUM LABELS PROVIDED A CONTACT WITH THE MANUFACTURER, WHO FAXED THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.  AS THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, THE ENTIRE LADING HAD TO BE REMOVED TO LOCATE THE SOURCE.  UPON REACHING THE NOSE ROW OF DRUMS, THE DRUM ON THE TOP LAYER, IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE DRUM DEVELOPED THE BOTTOM CHIME HAD THREE SMALL FLAT SPOTS WITHIN AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 2 INCHES. THE CENTER FLAT SPOT ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CHIME HAD A HAIR LINE CRACK THAT ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT.  IT APPEARS THIS CHIME DAMAGE WAS DONE PRIOR TO LOADING AS THERE WERE NO PROTRUSIONS IN THE PLYWOOD SEPARATOR THAT WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. BASED UPON THE WEIGHT OF OF THE DRUM, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT LESS THAN 1-2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ESCAPED.  THE CONTAINER WAS DECONNED AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK IN THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT PENDING RETURN SHIPPING INFORMATION FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  THE LADING WAS SECURED AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE PARKING STALL WAS ALSO REMEDIATED AND THE AREA OPENED FOR USE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ICTF SECURITY AND DEVELOPED THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN THE ROADWAY 805 SECTION, STALL NUMBER 120.  A SMALL AREA OF THE PAVEMENT SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS, AND APPEARED TO BE LESS THAN ONE PINT OF MATERIAL, WHICH HAD DRIED. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED TOXIC, THE AREA WAS SECURED TO PREVENT THROUGH TRAFFIC AND ISOLATED UNTIL IT COULD BE INSPECTED. AS MANAGER COOPER WAS OUT OF TOWN, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL RESPOND AND EVALUATE THE CONDITION OF THE CONTAINER.  ONCE THE TEAM WAS ON SITE, IT WAS DETERMINED THE CONTAINER COULD BE MOVED TO THE CUSTOMER'S DOCK FOR AN IN DEPTH INSPECTION OF THE INNER LADING.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, IT WAS NOTED THE CONTENTS TO BE DOUBLE STACKED METAL DRUMS SECURED WITH TY-PATCH MATERIAL.  THE DRUMS WERE SEPARATED ON THE BILEVEL WITH 1/2 INCH PLYWOOD.  THE CONTENTS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION AND THE TY-PATCH APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PROPERLY APPLIED.  INFORMATION FROM THE DRUM LABELS PROVIDED SHIPPER CONTACT AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  UPON REMOVING THE TWO ROWS OF DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER, THE FLOOR LOADED DRUM IN THE SECOND ROW AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER APPEARED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS HAD BEEN PLACED ON SHEETS OF PLYWOOD THAT COVERED THE FLOOR.  WITH THIS EXTRA ELEVATION, THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM HAD ABRADED THE ROUGH WELD IN THE CORRUGATED SIDEWALL WHERE THE "D" RING IS ATTACHED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS DEPRESSION IN THE SIDEWALL ALLOWS THE DRUM TO SIT WITH THE CHIME SLIGHTLY INDENTED INTO THE SIDEWALL, ALLOWING FOR CONTACT WITH THE "D" RING.  THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CHIME ABRADED THE ROUGH WELD WHICH CAUSED THE INSIDE OF THE CHIME TO DEVELOP A CRACK, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO SEEP.  THE SIDE PORTION OF THE ALSO SHOWED SIGNS OF ABRADING THE UPPER PORTION OF THE "D" RING AND WHILE THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF THINNING METAL, THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT AT THIS POINT OF CONTACT.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY  DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  BASED UPON THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT LESS THAN 1-2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ESCAPED.  THE CONTAINER WAS DECONNED AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT PENDING RETURN SHIPPING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  THE LADING WAS SECURED AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE PARKING STALL WAS ALSO REMEDIATED AND THE AREA OPENED FOR NORMAL USE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DRIVER WAS AT GAS STATION UNLOADING GASOLINE. HE HAD AREA OF DROPS BLOCKED OFF WITH ORANGE A CONE. A LADY IN PASSENGER CAR WANTED TO TAKE A SHORTCUT THRU PARKING LOT SO SHE RAN OVER THE CONES AND DID NOT STOP UNTIL HER CAR GOT HUNG UP ON  DROPP FITTING. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF VALVES AND TOLD THE LADY NOT TO MOVE BUT SHE PROCEDED TO TRY AND GET HER CAR OFF FITTING AND BROKE IT RESULTING IN GASOLINE SPILLAGE.
